{
  "doc_id": "52056",
  "text": "Profiling of methylated genes is growing rapidly as a powerful diagnostic tool for the early detection, prognosis and even prediction of clinical response to treatment of various cancer types [CITATION_1] . This encourages the search for new candidate genes using global demethylation and microarray analysis that could effectively find genes silenced in association with promoter hypermethylation in several tumor types, including CRC, with a role in cell proliferation, tumor progression, apoptosis or angiogenesis [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In CRC, the path of epigenetic silencing has not yet been fully explored and further searches for methylationsilenced genes are required. Despite the fact that hundreds of genes have been identified to be silenced through promoter CpG island methylation in CRC [CITATION_5] .",
